## Behavioral contract ‚Äî every session, before acting
1. **Load first, propose second.** Read `{{NAME}}.md` + `decisions.md` + the active
   workstream, the lesson modules whose "load when‚Ä¶" matches the task, the relevant **experiment
   records** when revisiting past runs/results, and any **linked global knowledge**
   (`config.json.knowledge` ‚Üí `$PROJECT_WITH_REFLECT_ROOT/knowledge/<k>`).
2. **Check the ledger before proposing.** If an idea/experiment is already in
   `decisions.md` or an experiment record, say so and cite it ‚Äî never re-propose or re-derive blind.
3. **Never improvise guarded state.** Datasets, training settings, branch/release
   conventions live in `lessons/` as invariants ‚Äî change only with explicit sign-off,
   then log it.
4. **Surface, don't bury.** When work touches an area with a lesson module or a
   registered eval, name it.
5. **Know your connections ‚Äî operate them skill-native.** For each name in `config.json.connections`,
   load `$PROJECT_WITH_REFLECT_ROOT/connections/<name>/connection.json` for the hard facts you need
   to orchestrate (transport, serial port/board, ssh alias, API base/key-env, MCP tools ‚Äî never
   guess a port, ssh target, or endpoint). But to actually *operate* a connection (flash / monitor /
   reconnect / call), go **through its own skill `/<name>`** ‚Äî it natively loads + applies its learned
   `## Quirks` (the gotchas + good practices `/<name> reflect` accrues), so this project inherits
   every other project's experience with that connection instead of rediscovering it. Don't
   re-implement a connection's behavior in the project or hand-read its quirk file ‚Äî delegate to its
   skill, the single place those quirks live and are applied.

## Working
Auto-log key events **as they happen** ‚Äî not batched at session end (a long session loses the early
details; `reflect`'s end-of-session capture is the **backstop**, not the plan) ‚Äî and **to the skill
the finding is about**, so knowledge lands where it's reusable:
- **Project finding** ‚Üí the active stream's `log.md`. Triggers: a **commit** (one line: what it
  accomplished + why, not the diff), **PR / merge / rebase**, a **decision** made (what + why ‚Äî
  reflect promotes it to `decisions.md`), a **long task finished** (a build / migration / refactor
  that took real effort ‚Äî outcome + any gotcha), an **experiment run + its result** (config ‚Üí metric ‚Üí
  verdict ‚Äî reflect promotes it to an experiment record), a **complex error + its fix**, a **key
  finding**. `note "‚Ä¶"` forces a line.
- **Connection finding** (a device / host / API quirk or workaround *any* project binding it would
  hit ‚Äî a flash boot-mode dance, an endpoint gotcha, "serial silent ‚âÝ crash") ‚Üí that connection's
  log via `/<name> note "‚Ä¶"`. Test: *would the next project that binds this connection need it?* ‚Üí
  connection's log; *only true for this app?* ‚Üí stream log. Device/API knowledge thus stays with the
  device/API (reusable across projects), not buried in one project's lessons.

**Record durable results the moment they land ‚Äî proactively, don't wait for `reflect`.** A *log* line is
ephemeral working memory (consumed at reflect). But a **durable, reusable result** ‚Äî a measured
**baseline / benchmark**, a **settled conclusion** ("X beats Y", "Œª=0 is visually bad"), an **experiment
verdict**, a hard-won **recipe / config** ‚Äî is painful to re-derive and easy to lose, so it belongs in
**permanent memory now**. When you produce one, **`record` it** (append to the right experiment record /
distilled lesson) and say where it landed ‚Äî don't just log it and hope reflect catches it. (Example: a
"GUAVA baseline on omni = PSNR 26.43 / ‚Ä¶" result ‚Üí `record` ‚Üí `lessons/experiment-GUAVA.md` immediately.)

## Subcommands
- `bootstrap` ‚Äî **seed this project from existing material** (run right after
  registering an existing project). Read the repo's docs (README, specs, CHANGELOG,
  design notes) across **every root** in `config.json.roots`, skim the codebase, and use the
  current conversation/session, then ‚Äî **for a remote project (`location: remote`) read those over the
  host connection** (`/<host_connection> 'cat <root>/README.md'`, `‚Ä¶ git -C <root> log --oneline`,
  `ls <root>`), never assuming local files ‚Äî then
  do an initial reflect-style pass: write the `lessons/<topic>.md` distilled modules + their index,
  capture any **past experiment results** that already exist (configs, run logs, metric tables) into
  a flat `lessons/experiment-<name>.md` record so they persist, populate `decisions.md` with the key choices already made,
  and write the `{{NAME}}.md` **narrative body** (the YAML frontmatter facts auto-generate ‚Äî run
  `gen-dashboard.sh {{PDIR}}` to refresh them; you write the prose below). Confirm
  what you captured ‚Äî distill, don't invent. **Replace any scaffold placeholder with real
  content; never leave boilerplate behind.**
- `status` ‚Äî print `{{NAME}}.md`.
- `list` ‚Äî handles: workstreams (+ lineage / behind-base), evals, tasks, lesson
  modules + experiment records, global knowledge used (`config.json.knowledge`).
- `help` ‚Äî this menu.
- `reflect [<target>] [--reground]` ‚Äî **`reflect` is log-and-reflect: it captures the session first,
  then distills** (aliases: `log-and-reflect`, and the top-level `/log-and-reflect` which resolves the
  project from your cwd ‚Äî all the same action). **Capture:** before folding,
  append this conversation's key events that aren't in the log yet to the right home (project finding ‚Üí
  the active stream's `log.md`; connection finding ‚Üí that connection's log ‚Äî see *Working*), at the
  auto-log bar (key events, not a verbose dump; idempotent ‚Äî already-logged events are skipped).
  **Directed reflect (with a `<target>`):** point reflect at any
  target ‚Äî a **code area** (`lib/auth`, "the dio retry logic"), a **repo skill** (`/e2e-iphone` ‚Äî just
  code that's team-shared), or a **lesson module / knowledge area** ‚Äî and it gathers the log entries
  about it and turns the logged experience into the right change *there*:
  - **code (incl. a repo skill)** ‚Üí reflect **flags a concrete dev item** from the log (what to
    change, where, why ‚Äî a fix, a guard, a preventive lesson, a small refactor) and records it.
    **Reflect does NOT edit the source itself** ‚Äî development is a separate, deliberate activity. It
    proceeds only when you **explicitly ask** *and* the **dev routine is clear** (which lane ‚Äî direct,
    or a workstream/worktree); the edit then runs through that lane (diff, commit/PR). A repo skill is
    just part of the codebase; its edit ships in the repo, so the whole team gets it.
  - **lesson / knowledge** ‚Üí fold into `lessons/`/`decisions.md` as usual.
  It distills the *logged experience* about the target, not a fresh codebase audit ‚Äî if little is
  logged, say so and offer a code-review pass instead. Then archive the consumed entries.
  **Plain `reflect` (no target):** triage first ‚Äî any new stream-log entry that's really about a bound
  connection (a device/API quirk, not this app) ‚Üí move it to that connection's `log.md` (it reflects
  into that connection's quirks via `/<name> reflect`), don't fold it into project lessons. Then route
  the remaining entries by **kind**:
  - **Accumulating records** (an experiment run + its config + metric + verdict; any running results
    table) ‚Üí **append to the relevant record lesson** (`lessons/experiment-<name>.md`, flat ‚Äî create if
    needed), **matching that lesson's established format** (same sections/columns/artifacts ‚Äî see the
    `record` action). **Append-only: never rewrite, consume, or archive these** ‚Äî they are the permanent
    record so numbers survive after host eval dirs get pruned. A settled *conclusion* drawn from them also
    goes to `decisions.md` (and a distilled lesson if it's a practice).
  - **Everything else** ‚Üí fold into the right `lessons/<topic>.md` distilled lesson + `decisions.md`
    (**bounded update**: add facts, fix wrong ones; **split a module** into another topic if it gets
    too long to read ‚Äî no caps).
  Then refresh the dashboard frontmatter facts (`gen-dashboard.sh {{PDIR}}`) and the `{{NAME}}.md`
  narrative body, then archive consumed **logs** (`reflect.sh archive {{PDIR}} <stream>` ‚Äî this archives
  the working `log.md` only, never the experiment records or lessons). Reflect stays **per-skill ‚Äî no
  cascade**: end by listing bound connections that have unreflected `log.md` lines and suggesting
  `/<name> reflect` for each. **Surface code/design flags (don't audit the source, don't fix
  silently):** reflect distills the *log*, not the codebase ‚Äî so flag what the log reveals: a module
  churned repeatedly, a workaround piled on a workaround, **the same failure recurring across runs
  (retried, never prevented)**, a "fix later". For each, **record a concrete code-development item**
  (todo / idea / task ‚Äî what to change, where, why; often a preventive lesson or a reordered procedure,
  not another retry). **Reflect stops there ‚Äî it flags, it does not edit the source.** The development
  is a separate activity you drive when ready: **direct**, a **workstream/worktree**, or **parked via
  `todo`** (a `## TODO` line in `{{NAME}}.md`, loaded every session so it resurfaces; a *repeatable*
  procedure ‚Üí `register-task`). Reflect makes the change itself **only if you explicitly ask and the
  dev routine is clear**.
  Report what changed. `--reground` = full grounding-rules-style rewrite of one distilled module
  (never an experiment record ‚Äî those are append-only).
- `streams` ‚Äî list `workstreams/*/stream.json`; flag any behind their `base`.
- `register-branch <b> --base <x> [--pr-into <y>] [--track-only] [--path <dir>]` ‚Äî run
  `register-branch.sh {{PDIR}} <b> ‚Ä¶` (deterministic git + `stream.json`; you just translate the
  intent into flags ‚Äî "v081 based on v080, just track" ‚Üí `v081 --base v080 --track-only`).
  `--track-only` records **lineage only, no git** (a version / integration branch you rebase onto);
  otherwise the lane is realized per `config.workstream_mode`: **worktree** ‚Üí `git worktree add`
  (needs `--path`; the script refuses with `PWR_NEED_WORKTREE_PATH` if absent ‚Üí ask the user for a
  clean dir, not sibling-clutter / not under `.claude/`), **in-repo** ‚Üí `git checkout -b` (HEAD
  switches, ready to work), **logical** ‚Üí no git. **Re-registering an existing lane** updates its
  `base`/`pr_into` only ‚Äî cycle / log / git untouched. The script generates the `/{{NAME}}-<b>` alias.
- `<branch>` (or "work on `<branch>`") ‚Äî switch to that workstream: load its `log.md` + `base` + lessons,
  then decide the **working dir** (the Bash cwd persists across calls, so wherever you land is where
  plan / scratch / planning-with-files files go). **Ask the user ‚Äî `cd` only on their choice:**
  - **Remote project** ‚Üí ask: switch into the lane's **workstream folder**
    `{{PDIR}}/workstreams/<branch>/` *(recommended ‚Äî keeps planning + working files in the vault, off
    the host and out of `~`)* **or stay**. The code stays on the host either way ‚Äî operate it via
    `/<host_connection>` over ssh.
  - **Local project** ‚Üí the **code dir** is the lane's `worktree_path` (worktree mode) else the repo.
    - If the session is **already inside the code dir** ‚Üí **do nothing** (no prompt ‚Äî you're where you
      should be).
    - Otherwise ask, three ways: switch to the **code dir** *(recommended)* / the **workstream folder**
      `{{PDIR}}/workstreams/<branch>/` / **stay**.
  After any switch, if planning-with-files is active, point its plan at the new dir so its files live
  there ‚Äî `reflect` then folds them into the log ‚Üí lessons.
  - `pr` ‚Äî rebase onto `base`; if `base` is behind ITS base
    (`git rev-list --count origin/<base>..origin/<base's base>` > 0) warn + offer
    to rebase the integration branch first; then `gh pr create --base <pr_into>`;
    log the PR + check. A merged stream is **reusable**: `reset` recycles it.
  - `rebase` ‚Äî `git rebase origin/<base>`.
  - `reset` ‚Äî after a merged PR, fast-forward the lane onto latest `origin/<base>`;
    bump `cycle` in `stream.json`.
- `register-eval <e> [path]` ‚Äî copy the case into `evals/<e>/`; generate
  `/{{NAME}}-<e>` (`gen-command.sh {{NAME}} <e> eval {{PDIR}}`). `eval all` runs
  the whole suite as a pre-release gate.
- `register-task <t>` ‚Äî save a runbook `tasks/<t>.md`; generate `/{{NAME}}-<t>`.
- `use-knowledge <k> [--unlink]` ‚Äî link a global knowledge module
  (`$PROJECT_WITH_REFLECT_ROOT/knowledge/<k>`) into this project ‚Äî the knowledge analog
  of binding a machine. Adds/removes `<k>` in `config.json.knowledge`
  (`link-knowledge.sh {{PDIR}} <k> [--unlink]`). One module can serve many projects;
  linked modules load when relevant (see the contract). Use after `/register-knowledge <k>`.
- `note "‚Ä¶"` ‚Äî force an **ephemeral** log line into the active stream (working memory, consumed at
  reflect). For a **durable** finding use `record` instead.
- `record ["<what>"]` ‚Äî **persist a durable thing into permanent memory NOW, in its right home**
  (not the ephemeral log ‚Äî that's `note`; not the end-of-session sweep ‚Äî that's `reflect`). **Flexible** ‚Äî
  it's not experiment-specific: you (or the user ‚Äî "record this as a rule", "record this website") infer
  or name the **kind**, then put it in the right **flat `lessons/<descriptive>.md`**:
  - **a result / benchmark / eval report** ‚Üí its record file (`lessons/experiment-GUAVA.md`,
    `lessons/experiment-baseline.md`) ‚Äî these **accumulate** (append the new run; don't rewrite history).
  - **a rule / must-follow practice / invariant / settled conclusion** ‚Üí a distilled lesson
    (`lessons/<topic>.md`, bounded update) + a line in `decisions.md` if it's a decision.
  - **a reference / resource / link** (a URL, a paper, a doc) ‚Üí a notes lesson (`lessons/resources.md`);
    if broadly reusable across projects, offer the global `$PROJECT_WITH_REFLECT_ROOT/knowledge/<k>`
    (`/register-knowledge` + `use-knowledge`) instead.
  - **a research report / review / etc.** ‚Üí its own lesson (`lessons/<name>.md`).
  - **anything else durable** ‚Üí the closest fitting lesson; ask only if genuinely ambiguous.

  **Follow the format of the lesson you're continuing ‚Äî for *any* kind, not just experiments.** When the
  thing you're recording **relates to or extends an existing lesson**, open it and **match its established
  structure** (its sections, columns, ordering, the way it embeds artifacts), then add the new entry ‚Äî so
  the lesson stays uniform and comparable over time: an experiment record's runs line up cell-for-cell
  (same axes / metrics / sub-targets, e.g. front/side/back √ó PSNR/SSIM/LPIPS √ó body/face/hand, grids
  embedded `![[‚Ä¶png]]` with frame key + metrics); a review follows the review format; new entries obey the
  writing rules. **The format is set by precedent + the user's tuning** ‚Äî the first entry of a kind
  establishes the shape (propose it; the user refines), and later entries follow it; if the user tunes the
  format, new entries follow the latest (don't retro-edit an append-only record ‚Äî note a format bump). If
  an artifact (a grid/image) matters, copy it into the vault and embed it so it survives host pruning.

  Bare `record` captures the latest durable thing from this session. Unlike `reflect`, `record` is
  **surgical and immediate** (one thing ‚Üí its home; archives nothing, runs no session sweep). **Be
  proactive** for results/conclusions (the moment you produce a baseline / benchmark / "X beats Y",
  record it and say where it landed); references/rules the user usually points you at. The user can
  always force or redirect: "record `<X>` as a `<kind>` in `<where>`".
- `todo ["<item>"] | done "<match>"` ‚Äî the project's lightweight backlog of pending dev items, kept as
  a checklist under `## TODO` in `{{NAME}}.md` (the dashboard ‚Äî loaded every session, so open items
  resurface and you can be offered them next time). `todo "<item>"` appends `- [ ] <item> ‚Äî <date>`;
  bare `todo` lists the open items; `todo done "<match>"` ticks it (`- [x]`). This is where reflect
  records a flagged change you **accept but defer**, and where you **manually park** work for later.
  `todo` only *tracks* ‚Äî doing the item is normal development (direct, or a workstream/worktree).
  Keep the section; reflect maintains it, never clobbers it.

### Connections (when bound)
A project binds the connections it operates (a serial device, an ssh box, an API, an MCP). Each
is also its own skill `/<name>`; from here you orchestrate them in project context.
- `bind --connection <name> [--build "<cmd>"] [--unbind <name>]` ‚Äî add/remove a connection in
  `config.json.connections`, or save the build command (`bind.sh {{PDIR}} ‚Ä¶`). `--device` /
  `--machine` are accepted aliases. Register it first (`/register-device|machine|api|mcp`).
- `build` ‚Äî run `config.json.build_cmd` if set; else derive it from the toolchain + repo, run it,
  and offer to save it via `bind --build "<cmd>"`.
- `flash` / `monitor` ‚Äî operate the bound **serial** connection **through its skill** (`/<name> flash`
  / `/<name> monitor`): it applies the device's quirks first, then runs its baked
  `$PROJECT_WITH_REFLECT_ROOT/connections/<name>/flash.sh` / `monitor.sh`. Auto-log the flash.
- A bound **ssh** connection ‚Üí operate via `/<name>` (deploy / run-remote / fetch-logs over its
  alias); **http/mcp** ‚Üí call / use via `/<name>`. Never hard-code a host, port, or endpoint, and
  don't bypass a connection's skill ‚Äî that's where its learned quirks get applied.

### Where a lesson lands
A lesson from the log can take several forms, and reflect routes by **what kind it is + who needs it**:
- **A code-development item** ‚Äî the fix belongs in the source: a `lib/` module, a config, or a
  **repo skill** (`.claude/commands|skills/‚Ä¶`, a team-shared doc like `/e2e-iphone` ‚Äî just part of the
  codebase). reflect **flags and records** it; **it does not make the change itself** ‚Äî the
  **development follows** as a separate step you drive (direct, or a workstream/worktree), and only on
  your explicit go-ahead with a clear routine. A repo-skill edit ships in the repo, so the whole team
  gets it.
- **Durable knowledge** ‚Äî so it isn't relearned. A project **lesson** (`lessons/`, your per-dev
  knowledge in the PWR root) or a **connection's quirks** (cross-project device/API knowledge).
- **An experiment result** ‚Äî a run's config + metric + verdict ‚Üí an **append-only record lesson**
  (`lessons/experiment-<name>.md`), so the number survives even after the host output is pruned.

Often a lesson is several at once: a flagged code change, a recorded invariant, *and* a result row. A
repo skill is just the case where the "code" is itself a shared skill doc ‚Äî nothing special beyond
living in `.claude/`.

Leanness: **no caps** ‚Äî keep distilled lessons readable; split a long module into another topic;
reflect makes bounded updates to them, not whole-doc rewrites. **Experiment records are the exception:
append-only and allowed to grow** ‚Äî keep them readable by splitting across files (per version/sweep),
never by deleting history.

Notes carry **content, not boilerplate**: clean headings, real decisions/lessons ‚Äî no
meta-instructions and no comment cruft in the files (that guidance lives in this skill).
Don't keep scaffold placeholders ‚Äî replace them with real content.

Note style: when the root is an **Obsidian vault**, write `lessons/` + `decisions.md` +
the `{{NAME}}.md` dashboard in clean Obsidian Flavored Markdown ‚Äî light frontmatter
`tags`, one `> [!note]` callout per note, `[[wikilinks]]` between these notes, and
**always backtick `<placeholders>`** (a bare `<x>` breaks rendering). Stay lean; don't
over-format. Otherwise plain Markdown.
